    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "subject to the constraint that:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b002",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 2,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}\n\\left|f_{i+1}-f_{i}\\right|<1.\n\\end{aligned} \\quad (15.13)"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b003",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 3,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "In other words, we optimize over a new set of variables $\\lbrace f_{i} \\rbrace$ where adjacent values cannot change by more than one."
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b004",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 4,
    "type": "heading",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "15.2.5 Wasserstein distance for continuous distributions"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b005",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 5,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "Translating these results back to the continuous multi-dimensional domain, the equivalent of the primal form (equation 15.10) is:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b006",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 6,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "Problems 15.4–15.5"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b007",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 7,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}\nD_{w}\\Big[Pr(\\mathbf{x}),q(\\mathbf{x})\\Big]=\\min_{\\pi[\\bullet,\\bullet]}\\left[\\iint\\pi(\\mathbf{x}_{1},\\mathbf{x}_{2})\\cdot||\\mathbf{x}_{1}-\\mathbf{x}_{2}||d\\mathbf{x}_{1}d\\mathbf{x}_{2}\\right],\n\\end{aligned} \\quad (15.14)"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b008",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 8,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "subject to constraints similar to equation 15.11 on the transport plan $\\pi(\\mathbf{x}_{1}, \\mathbf{x}_{2})$ representing the mass moved from position $\\mathbf{x}_{1}$ to $\\mathbf{x}_{2}$. The equivalent of the dual form (equation 15.12) is:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b009",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 9,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "Appendix B.1.1 Lipschitz constant"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b010",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 10,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}\nD_{w}\\Big[Pr(\\mathbf{x}),q(\\mathbf{x})\\Big]=\\max_{\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{x}]}\\left[\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{x}]d\\mathbf{x}-\\int q(\\mathbf{x})f[\\mathbf{x}]d\\mathbf{x}\\right],\n\\end{aligned} \\quad (15.15)"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b011",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 11,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "subject to the constraint that the Lipschitz constant of the function f[x] is less than one (i.e., the absolute gradient of the function is less than one)."
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b012",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 12,
    "type": "heading",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "15.2.6 Wasserstein GAN loss function"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b013",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 13,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "In the context of neural networks, we maximize over the space of functions f[x] by optimizing the parameters $\\phi$ in a neural network f[x, $\\phi$ ], and we approximate these integrals using generated samples $x_{i}^{*}$ and real examples $x_{i}$ :"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b014",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 14,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}L[\\phi]\\quad&=\\quad\\sum_{j}\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{x}_{j}^{*},\\boldsymbol{\\phi}]-\\sum_{i}\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{x}_{i},\\boldsymbol{\\phi}]\\\\&=\\quad\\sum_{j}\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{g}[z_{j},\\boldsymbol{\\theta}],\\boldsymbol{\\phi}]-\\sum_{i}\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{x}_{i},\\boldsymbol{\\phi}],\\end{aligned} \\quad (15.16)"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b015",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 15,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "where we must constrain the neural network discriminator $f[x,\\phi]$ to have an absolute gradient norm of less than one at every position x:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b016",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 16,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}\n\\left|\\frac{\\partial\\mathrm{f}[\\mathbf{x},\\boldsymbol{\\phi}]}{\\partial\\mathbf{x}}\\right|<1.\n\\end{aligned} \\quad (15.17)"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0286-b017",
    "page_key": 286,
    "order": 17,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "One way to achieve this is to clip the discriminator weights to a small range (e.g., $\\pm0.01$ ). An alternative is the gradient penalty Wasserstein GAN or WGAN-GP, which adds a regularization term that increases as the gradient norm deviates from unity."
  }
]
